The getter method isEmeddable is misspelled. It should be isEmbeddable (with two 'b's in "Embeddable").
Details
// Current code:
```
get isEmeddable() {
  return this.isSnippet ? this.isPublished : true;
}
```
Correct spelling:
```
get isEmbeddable() {
  return this.isSnippet ? this.isPublished : true;
}
```
 Why it matters
This typo can cause confusion or bugs when attempting to check if the content is embeddable using content.isEmbeddable. Since the method is misnamed, any reference to the correctly spelled version will return undefined.

In the [TF-IDF article](https://www.30secondsofcode.org/js/s/tf-idf-inverted-index/), the [first example in Arbitrary Search section](https://www.30secondsofcode.org/js/s/tf-idf-inverted-index/#arbitrary-search) appears to have a unnecessary call of `removeStopwords` in `parseDocument` as shown below:

```javascript
const parseDocument = document => {
  const tokens = removeStopwords(commonStopWords, tokenize(document)); // I believe this should be `tokenize(document)`
  const filteredTokens = removeStopwords(commonStopWords, tokens);
  const stemmedTokens = filteredTokens.map(porterStemmer);
  return stemmedTokens;
}
```

I don't think this extra call would do any harm, but it might be confusing for the reader.

